Risksimtable allows you to view a distribution of results rather than just one result. It compares items such as the mean, standard deviation, maximum, minimum etc. All theses things can help a company make it the best possible.

An example of a simulation and how we would use risksimtable is the Walton, the example we did in class. First you had to put all the given information in excel to create the model, then you had to decide which order quatitites we wanted to test, then we had to use the risksimtable to put different quatities that we wanted to simulate, after that we ran the simulation by doing iterations of 5. Finally the report comes up showing the different simulations, and the one that would be ideal to pick is the one with a low standard deviation and high mean (expected value).
